      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:55:42.498128+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "749aab08",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 2) SAR REASONING (why these features push hERG up/down)\n### Features increasing hERG likelihood\n1. **Permanent/strong cation at pH 7.4**  \n   hERG blockers often form a key **electrostatic interaction** in the pore (classically with residues in the inner cavity) and benefit from being **protonated**.\n2. **Two aromatic/hydrophobic regions around the basic center**  \n   hERG\u2019s cavity is **hydrophobic/aromatic-friendly**; aromatic rings can engage in **\u03c0/van der Waals** interactions and help anchor the ligand.\n3. **Flexibility and appropriate reach**  \n   Ether/alkyl linkers allow conformations that can place the **cation** and **aryl groups** into the channel cavity in a productive geometry.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:55:42.498151+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "25271c81",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### Features decreasing hERG likelihood\n1. **Sulfonamide increases polarity / H-bonding and reduces lipophilicity**  \n   Many potent hERG blockers are quite lipophilic; adding a sulfonamide often **reduces passive partitioning** and can reduce affinity by shifting the ligand toward more solvated conformations.\n2. **Primary ammonium (vs tertiary amine) nuance**  \n   Many high-risk hERG binders are **tertiary amines** (often higher lipophilicity and better cavity fit). A **primary ammonium** can still block hERG, but sometimes with **reduced potency** due to higher hydration penalty and different steric profile.",
      "tool_name": null,
